dataIdInfo.idPurp: This line dataset was created to show the Road features in Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks. It is used for mapping and analysis purposes.
dataIdInfo.idAbs: This is a vector line dataset representing the Road features in and near Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks. This dataset is utilizing the updated NPS Road Spatial Data Standard as existing in January 2018. This dataset originated as USGS DLG line features from the original 7.5' topo quads. Over the years various updates have taken place as source info and GPS has improved. Some of the latest updates to trails come from Lidar data acquired in 2015 and 2016 in the areas of Giant Sequoia groves.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: National Park Service, Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks GIS, Pacific West Region

attr.attrdef: Current physical state of the road or road segment (FS Travel Routes Data Dictionary, 2009).

edom.edomvd: Road exists, is open to the public, and is physically present and observable.
Road exists, but is seasonally closed, closed for repairs, or closed due to a hazard. Intent is that the road will reopen at a later date.
A road that was no longer needed and has been removed from service. The road has been permanently closed or altered to return to natural state.
Planned road identified by an appropriate management decision (e.g. NEPA). Also used to describe the road during the construction phase until it becomes open to the public.
Road is proposed and no management decision has been made (e.g. NEPA).
Road status is unknown.

attr.attrdef: The grouping of roads by the character of service they provide (US Census Bureau MTFCC, 2009).

edom.edomvd: Primary roads are generally divided, limited-access highways within the interstate highway system or under state management, and are distinguished by the presence of interchanges. These highways are accessible by ramps and may include some toll highways. (MTFCC Code S1100)

Secondary roads are main arteries, usually in the U.S. Highway, State Highway or County Highway system. These roads have one or more lanes of traffic in each direction, may or may not be divided, and usually have at-grade intersections with many other roads and driveways. They often have both a local name and a route number. (MTFCC Code S1200)

Generally a paved non-arterial street, road, or byway that usually has a single lane of traffic in each direction. Roads in this feature class may be privately or publicly maintained. Scenic park roads would be included in this feature class, as would (depending on the region of the country) some unpaved roads. (MTFCC Code S1400)
An unpaved dirt road where a four-wheel drive vehicle is required. These vehicular roads are found almost exclusively in very rural areas. (MTFCC Code S1500)
These roads can be named and may intersect with other roads for access roads to, or within an industrial estate, campsite, business park, car park etc. (MTFCC Code S1640)

A road that is maintained for administrative service, extractive, or other purposes. These roads are often unnamed. Agency use road only, not open for the public. Restricted to Agency Concurrence and Distribution is No to the public but the individual parks should use discretion with public maps produced by the parks service. (MTFCC Code S1740)
The main travel route for vehicles through a paved parking area.
Road class is unknown

attr.attrdef: The wearing course; usually designed to resist skidding, traffic abrasion, and the disintegrating effects of weather (FS Travel Routes Data Dictionary, 2009 and FMSS, 2016).

edom.edomvd: Asphalt, is a composite material commonly used for construction of pavement, highways and parking lots.

A concrete surface is constructed of Portland cement concrete, sometimes with embedded iron reinforcement bars. Concrete is considered a “rigid” surface since it does not deform with the movement of the underlying base and sub base.

Interlocking masonry blocks placed to form the wearing surface. Paving stones are equally sized concrete stones, with a flat top. They are comparable to flattened cobblestones (and often used in the same cases), but the gaps between the paving stones are smaller because the stones have a perfectly regular shape (rectangular, or any surface-filling shape). Paving stones are often found in low-traffic streets (like pedestrian zones) because they can't endure heavy traffic.

Small one- to two-inch stones placed in a sand, asphalt or concrete matrix to form the wearing surface. Cobblestone paving. "Cobblestone" is used in the colloquial meaning and includes the type of stones that would more precisely be called "setts".

Surfaces of crushed aggregate (gravel, without asphalt). Broken/crushed rock with sharp edges, known as ballast on railways. Usually loosely arranged. Typical size for road and surface construction range between 4 and 8 cm.
Small to very small fractions (less than 2mm) of rock.
Native surface material generally the terrain composition that the road travels through; not imported material.
Other paved surface.
Other unpaved surface.
Road surface is unknown.

attr.attrdef: Direction of one way roads. Use GIS software to define direction when symbolized.

edom.edomvd: With direction of digitization: the direction of travel is the same as the direction the line was created in mapping software (from the first “vertex” to the “last” vertex).
Against direction in which the line was digitized: the direction of travel is the opposite as the direction the line was created in mapping software (from the last “vertex” to the “first” vertex).

attr.attrdef: The maximum number of lanes existing on a road element (FGDC Transportation, 2008 and US Department of Transportation FHWA, 2013).

The ID-number of a particular route in a given road network as attributed by a national, sub-national or international organization (IE. Federal, state or county). Can be used for labeling purposes using “shields”. Value must have a space between designation and number. Values will be Pipe-delimited for routes that share several numerical designations (FGDC Transportation, 2008).
Example: US 441 | County 66 | SH 14

Examples: Western Arctic Parklands; Southwest Alaska Inventory and Monitoring Network
The alpha code of the NPS Region.

Date the feature was initially created.
Example: 02/17/2015

The person who initially created the feature.
Example: John Smith

Date the feature was last edited.
Example: 02/17/2015

The person who last edited the feature.
Example: John Smith

How the geospatial feature was derived.

The date of the source material.

An estimate of the measurement error in the horizontal (ASPRS, 2014).

edom.edomvd: Data of unknown origin, spatial accuracy, unknown scale or resolution where a minimum mapping unit or scale of reference cannot be statistically determined (Qualitative accuracy assessment). Examples: Legacy data with little or no spatial attribute information.

Survey-grade mapping with a dual-frequency carrier phase GPS/GNSS receiver used for survey monumentation, vertical assessments, boundary surveys, and SET positions. Often a result of a Real-time Kinematic (RTK), Real-time Network (RTN), Static GNSS surveys or traditional survey methods. Examples: Trimble R10,R8,R6 RTK Systems; Javad Triumph 1,2 RTK Systems; EOS Arrow 200 w/ Real-time Network; Nikon 5” Total Station; Trimble S6 Total Station

Resource-grade mapping with a dual-frequency GPS/GNSS receiver likely combined with a dual-frequency antenna using differential corrections. Some Lidar data. Examples: Trimble GeoXH; EOS Arrow 200; Trimble Pathfinder Office/TerraSync w/ differential correction

Resource-grade mapping with a differential-capable GPS/GNSS receiver using differential corrections. Examples: Trimble GeoXT/Geo7X; EOS Arrow 100; Trimble Pathfinder Office/TerraSync w/ differential correction
Mapping with any GPS/GNSS satellite real-time receiver likely corrected with WAAS. Examples: Garmin handheld w/ WAAS; Trimble Juno handheld; EOS Arrow Lite

Mapping with an autonomous GPS/GNSS or location-based services (LBS) receiver designed for recreational or consumer use. Data that are heads-up digitized from sources such as 1:24,000. Examples: Handheld Cellular Device; GPS Watch

At greater (coarser) than 1:24,000 scale, the National Standard for Spatial Data Accuracy (NSSDA) is 13.9 meters with 95% accuracy (ASPRS, 2005). Examples: Heads up digitizing using an old 1:100000 scale NAD 27 map; GPS collected point under heavy canopy

Map selected; nominal accuracy based on geo-referenced background (imagery or map) data scale; refer to metadata of the specific geo-referenced background data used for a better idea of its spatial accuracy. Any hand-digitized data using background imagery such as from NAIP2015, USDA FSA, or other sources.

attr.attrdef:
NPS-UNITCODE-ROUTENUMBER. This ID is a Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) identifier that was created for the Road Inventory Program (RIP). This is a unique identifier that can be used to relate to RIP data. The route number contained within this ID is also related to a FMSS road functional class and must be four characters minimum. See Table 7.
Example: NPS-GOGA-0223

Indicates feature or features that are no longer in existence or partially in existence. If data represents features that are no longer in existence or only partially in existence following damage, disaster or some other change to its status then the value will be false or partial (Cultural Resources, 2014).
